We have seen in §  how to obtain principles for equational reasoning by imposing path object structures on types; in general, we will need an analogous tool for working with families of types B\colon  
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\to \mathsf {Type} given a path object \mathcal {A}. Such a tool must account for heterogeneous identifications in B, i.e. identifications between elements of different fibers of B; in this section, we explore three possible variations on the concept of “dependent path object”:

A displayed reflexive graph \mathcal {B} over a reflexive graph \mathcal {A} is called univalent when for each x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 the component \mathcal {B}
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrack x\right \rbrack \mathclose {}
 is univalent. We define a displayed path object to be a univalent displayed reflexive graph.

Let \mathcal {A} be a path object, and let \mathcal {B}\colon 
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\to \mathsf {PathObj} be a family of path objects. A left cleaving of \mathcal {B} over \mathcal {A} is given by the following data:

